-- allium: 3
-- turbo-kv-4b.allium

-- Scope: TurboQuant 4-bit KV cache quantisation — the core algorithm
-- plus its practical SOTA adaptations for LLM KV cache use.
--
-- Citable sources (use throughout this file):
--
--   [PAPER]       Zandieh, Daliri, Hadian, Mirrokni. "TurboQuant:
--                 Online Vector Quantization with Near-optimal
--                 Distortion Rate." ICLR 2026. arxiv 2504.19874.
--                 Prescribes: random orthogonal rotation 𝚷 ∈ ℝ^(d×d)
--                 applied to the full d-dimensional input, Lloyd-Max
--                 codebook with centroids c₁..c₂ᵇ ∈ [-1, 1] solved
--                 ONCE per bit-width (reused across dimensions), and
--                 for inner-product estimation (attention) a two-
--                 stage MSE+QJL construction. Paper's experiments
--                 use d=1536, 3072 (OpenAI3 embedding dimensions);
--                 the paper does NOT validate on LLM KV cache head
--                 dimensions.
--
--   [QUANT.CPP]   quantumaikr/quant.cpp (Apache-2.0), the C
--                 reference implementation our llama.cpp port
--                 inherits from. Implements "Variant F" of the
--                 paper's algorithm: codebook-only (no QJL),
--                 per-128-element block rotation (NOT per-head),
--                 max_abs-based per-block rescale, fixed Lloyd-Max-
--                 Gaussian codebooks with centroids extending
--                 beyond [-1, 1]. Variant F's design comment:
--                 "Karpathy-loop ablation: QJL contributed ~0.
--                 Reclaimed those 16 bytes to upgrade codebook
--                 resolution."
--                 See include/turboquant/tq_types.h,
--                 src/core/tq_turbo_kv.c.
--
--   [TONBI-V3]    tonbistudio/turboquant-pytorch compressors_v3.py.
--                 Community PyTorch implementation. Declares:
--                 "We implemented the paper's algorithm, found that
--                 its key innovation (QJL) actually hurts in
--                 practice, and built an improved version (V3)
--                 informed by findings from 8+ independent
--                 community implementations." Per-head d×d rotation
--                 (matches paper), MSE-only codebook, no inv_std
--                 rescale, **residual window** (keep recent N
--                 tokens in fp16), asymmetric K/V bit-widths, and
--                 layer-adaptive precision.
--
-- This file describes the core paper algorithm (rotation +
-- codebook) plus the Variant F simplifications we inherit (no QJL,
-- per-block adaptation). Sibling specs cover the remaining
-- community improvements:
--   - turbo_kv_residual_window.allium      (tonbi-v3)
--   - turbo_kv_asymmetric.allium           (paper §4 + tonbi-v3)
--   - turbo_kv_layer_adaptive.allium       (tonbi-v3)
--   - turbo_kv_outliers.allium             (quant.cpp 4bo / 3bo)
-- Each of those specs adds a composable layer onto this core.
--
-- Goal (per project direction): SOTA for PPL and speed on LLM KV
-- cache, not paper verbatim. Where [PAPER] and community evidence
-- disagree, we follow the empirical community consensus and cite
-- the evidence that justifies the departure.
--
-- Includes: head quantise / dequantise, RHT forward / inverse,
-- L2_norm, normalize, rescale, nearest_centroid, reconstruct_codebook.
-- Excludes:
--   - SIMD / backend implementations (AVX2, Vulkan, CUDA, ROCm,
--     ARM) — implementation detail. Sister specs cover per-backend
--     equivalence.
--   - 3-bit variant — separate file (turbo-kv-3b.allium).
--   - Residual window, asymmetric K/V, layer-adaptive, outlier
--     handling — separate files as listed above. Their application
--     composes on top of this core.

-- ============================================================
-- External entities (managed by the model's tensor system)
-- ============================================================

external entity Tensor {
    data: Set<Decimal>
    count: Integer
}

actor TensorSupplier {
    identified_by: Tensor
}

-- ============================================================
-- Value types
-- ============================================================

-- One quantised attention-head row. [PAPER] §3 compress step
-- produces a (norm, indices) pair. [QUANT.CPP] Variant F's wire
-- format additionally stores a per-block inv_std field because it
-- uses a Gaussian(0, 1) codebook rather than paper's [-1, 1]
-- codebook and needs to rescale rotated values to fit the codebook
-- range — included below so wire-format equivalence specs can
-- check it.
entity QuantizedHead {
    norm: Decimal          -- L2 norm of the pre-normalisation head row
    inv_std: Decimal       -- [QUANT.CPP] Variant F rescale factor;
                           -- paper has no such field (its codebook
                           -- lives in [-1, 1] matching the unit-sphere
                           -- rotated input distribution).
    indices: Set<Integer>  -- head_dim codebook indices, each in [0, codebook_size)
}

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- Head dimension. [PAPER] does not validate at LLM KV head
    -- sizes (paper tests d=1536, 3072 on OpenAI3 embeddings).
    -- Production Qwen3.5 values are 128 (0.8B) and 256 (9B, 35B).
    -- [QUANT.CPP] Variant F hardcodes block size to TQ_BK = 128,
    -- which agrees with the paper's full-vector rotation when
    -- head_dim = 128 and splits into 2 independent sub-blocks
    -- when head_dim = 256. The multi-block split is a [QUANT.CPP]
    -- departure, not a paper prescription. [TONBI-V3] uses per-head
    -- d×d rotation consistent with the paper.
    head_dim: Integer = 128

    -- Bits per quantised coordinate. Fixed to 4 for this spec file.
    bits: Integer = 4

    -- Codebook size = 2^bits. [PAPER] §3: "Construct codebook by
    -- finding centroids c₁, c₂, … c_{2^b} ∈ [-1, 1] that minimize
    -- MSE cost… store the results for future uses." ONE codebook
    -- per bit-width, reused across dimensions.
    codebook_size: Integer = 16

    -- Seed for the random orthogonal rotation. [PAPER] requires
    -- random orthogonal — any draw from the uniform Haar measure
    -- on O(d) works. A Hadamard matrix composed with random ±1
    -- sign flips (Fast Hadamard Transform plus sign randomisation)
    -- is a fast approximation at O(d log d) cost; [QUANT.CPP] and
    -- our llama.cpp port use this. [TONBI-V3] uses a dense Gaussian-
    -- orthogonal matrix at O(d²) from QR decomposition.
    seed: Integer = 305419896  -- 0x12345678

    -- Empirical tolerance for norm-preservation in reconstruction.
    -- [QUANT.CPP] ablations on unit Gaussian at head_dim=128 give
    -- rel_err ≈ 0.083; 0.1 is a ~20% safety margin.
    reconstruction_rel_error: Decimal = 0.1

    -- [QUANT.CPP] Variant F codebook range. The Lloyd-Max Gaussian
    -- (not unit-sphere) codebook has centroids in [-cent_max,
    -- cent_max] with this value as the outermost centroid. Rotated
    -- values are rescaled by inv_std = cent_max / max_abs to fit.
    -- [PAPER] has no analogous constant (its centroids live in
    -- [-1, 1] matching the unit-sphere input range).
    cent_max: Decimal = 2.7326
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open questions
-- ============================================================

-- [PAPER] prescribes QJL for inner-product estimation (attention).
-- Quote from arxiv 2504.19874 §3: "we propose a two-stage approach:
-- applying an MSE quantizer followed by a 1-bit Quantized JL (QJL)
-- transform on the residual." Both [QUANT.CPP] Variant F and
-- [TONBI-V3] drop QJL based on independent empirical ablations.
-- [QUANT.CPP] commit log: "Karpathy-loop ablation: QJL contributed
-- ~0. Reclaimed those 16 bytes." [TONBI-V3] README: "QJL actually
-- hurts in practice… QJL variance is amplified by softmax, hurting
-- attention." Our llama.cpp port inherits the QJL drop. This is a
-- community-led improvement over [PAPER] and the spec reflects that.
open question "QJL residual for attention: paper requires it; two independent community ablations show it hurts quality. Spec currently matches community consensus (no QJL). If future measurement contradicts the community finding, QJL would be added as a sibling improvement spec."

-- [QUANT.CPP] Variant F uses a fixed 128-element block regardless
-- of head_dim; for head_dim > 128 this splits a head into
-- blocks_per_head = head_dim / 128 sub-blocks, each with its own
-- rotation, its own max_abs, and its own inv_std. This is NOT
-- [PAPER]'s prescription — [PAPER] §3 applies the rotation to the
-- full d-dimensional vector. [TONBI-V3] implements per-head d×d
-- rotation. The 9B IQ3_XXS PPL data
-- (reference/ppl/results/Qwen3.5-9B-UD-IQ3_XXS) shows turbo_kv_4b
-- +0.23 PPL above F16 baseline — this spec attributes that gap to
-- the multi-block split at head_dim=256 rather than to any GPU
-- kernel bug (confirmed by turbo_kv_4b_attention.allium's
-- propagated PBT: CPU FA vs Vulkan FA pass within fp32 tolerance).
open question "Rotation granularity: paper and tonbistudio V3 use full d×d (per-head); quant.cpp Variant F uses fixed 128-element sub-blocks. The port inherits Variant F. For head_dim > 128 the sub-block split loses cross-block correlation — the observed cost at 9B head_dim=256 is +0.23 PPL vs F16. Fixing this requires restructuring the port to do one d×d rotation per head."

-- [QUANT.CPP] Variant F's inv_std + Gaussian codebook is
-- mathematically different from [PAPER]'s direct-argmin +
-- [-1, 1] codebook. Both are valid Lloyd-Max quantisers on
-- different parameterisations of the rotated-unit-sphere
-- distribution. Quality should be similar at d = codebook training
-- dim; may diverge at other d.
open question "Codebook parameterisation: paper uses one codebook in [-1,1] per bit-width, trained against the unit-sphere rotated distribution. Quant.cpp uses N(0,1) Lloyd-Max centroids extending past ±1 with per-block max_abs rescaling. These are mathematically different but may perform comparably when the codebook's training distribution matches the input."

-- Asymmetric key/value bit-widths — [PAPER] §4 discusses
-- asymmetric allocation; [TONBI-V3] measures K6/V4 rw=128 as
-- "EXACT" (perfect needle-retrieval) while symmetric K4/V4 rw=0
-- is "MISS" (garbage output). The port is symmetric K=V=4-bit
-- with no residual window — the worst of the measured configs
-- in [TONBI-V3]'s table.
open question "Asymmetric K/V bit allocation: paper §4 discusses and tonbistudio V3 measures K6/V4 as the quality sweet spot. Our port uses symmetric K=V=4-bit. This is a sibling-spec concern (turbo_kv_asymmetric.allium); noted here for visibility."

-- ============================================================
-- Algorithm-level rules
-- ============================================================

rule L2_norm {
    when: L2_norm(data)

    let norm_sq = sum_of_squares(data)
    let result = sqrt(norm_sq)

    ensures: result >= 0.0
}

rule normalize {
    when: normalize(data, norm)

    requires: norm > 0.0

    let inv_norm = 1.0 / norm
    let result = scaled(data, inv_norm)

    ensures: L2_norm(result) = 1.0
}

rule rescale {
    when: rescale(data, norm)

    requires: norm >= 0.0

    let result = scaled(data, norm)

    ensures: L2_norm(result) = L2_norm(data) * norm
}

-- [PAPER] §3: random rotation 𝚷 ∈ ℝ^(d×d) applied to the full
-- input vector. Any draw from the Haar measure on O(d) works.
-- [QUANT.CPP] Variant F and our port approximate this via
-- FHT + random ±1 signs at O(d log d) cost. [TONBI-V3] uses a
-- dense Gaussian-orthogonal matrix from QR. Distributional
-- equivalence is what matters for the Lloyd-Max distortion
-- bound, not the specific construction.
rule RHT_forward {
    when: RHT_forward(data, n, seed)

    requires: n > 0

    let n2 = floor_pow2(n)
    let with_signs = apply_sign_flip(data, n2, seed)
    let hadamarded = walsh_hadamard_transform(with_signs, n2)
    let result = scale(hadamarded, 1.0 / sqrt(n2), n2)

    ensures: result.length = n
}

rule RHT_inverse {
    when: RHT_inverse(data, n, seed)

    requires: n > 0

    let n2 = floor_pow2(n)
    let scaled_data = scale(data, 1.0 / sqrt(n2), n2)
    let hadamarded = walsh_hadamard_transform(scaled_data, n2)
    let result = apply_sign_flip(hadamarded, n2, seed)

    ensures: result.length = n
}

-- Per-element argmin against the codebook. [PAPER] §3
-- (compress): indices[i] = argmin_c |rotated[i] - centroids[c]|.
-- [QUANT.CPP] Variant F additionally rescales rotated values by
-- inv_std before argmin so that the Gaussian(0,1) Lloyd-Max
-- codebook fits the dynamic range; this is in the port. [TONBI-V3]
-- omits this step (codebook in [-1, 1] matches the unit-sphere
-- input range natively). Spec models the [QUANT.CPP] flavour
-- because that's what our llama.cpp port implements.
rule nearest_centroid {
    when: nearest_centroid(rotated_data, inv_std, codebook_entries)

    requires: codebook_entries.count > 0

    let scaled_data = scaled_vector(rotated_data, inv_std)
    let result = find_nearest(scaled_data, codebook_entries)

    ensures: result.count = rotated_data.count
}

-- Codebook lookup + inverse of the inv_std rescale so the
-- reconstructed values land back in the rotated-unit-sphere space.
rule reconstruct_codebook {
    when: reconstruct_codebook(block, codebook_entries)

    requires: codebook_entries.count > 0
    requires: block.indices.count > 0
    requires: block.inv_std > 0.0

    let scale = 1.0 / block.inv_std
    let lut = scaled_codebook(codebook_entries, scale)
    let result = lookup_indices(block.indices, lut, block.indices.count)

    ensures: result.count = block.indices.count
}

-- ============================================================
-- Composite rules
-- ============================================================

-- End-to-end head quantise, matching the [QUANT.CPP] Variant F
-- pipeline that our llama.cpp port implements:
--   norm     = L2_norm(x)
--   rotated  = RHT(x / norm)
--   inv_std  = cent_max / max_abs(rotated)
--   indices  = argmin_c |rotated[i] * inv_std - centroids[c]|  per i
--   store (norm, inv_std, indices)
rule QuantizeHead {
    when: QuantizeHead(tensor, seed)

    requires: tensor.count = config.head_dim
    requires: L2_norm(tensor.data) > 0.0

    let norm = L2_norm(tensor.data)
    let normalized = normalize(tensor.data, norm)
    let rotated = RHT_forward(normalized, config.head_dim, config.seed)
    let max_val = max_abs(rotated)
    let inv_std = config.cent_max / max_val
    let indices = nearest_centroid(rotated, inv_std, turbo_kv_4b_codebook)

    ensures: QuantizedHead.created(
        norm: norm,
        inv_std: inv_std,
        indices: indices
    )
}

rule DequantizeHead {
    when: DequantizeHead(block)

    requires: block.inv_std > 0.0
    requires: block.indices.count = config.head_dim

    let codebook_values = reconstruct_codebook(block, turbo_kv_4b_codebook)
    let dequant_rotated = RHT_inverse(codebook_values, config.head_dim, config.seed)
    let reconstructed = rescale(dequant_rotated, block.norm)

    ensures: Tensor.created(
        data: reconstructed,
        count: config.head_dim
    )
}

-- [PAPER] §3 identity: dot(q, dequant(block)) = dot(RHT(q), lut(indices)) * norm
-- because RHT is orthogonal. The port uses this to pre-rotate the
-- query once per attention call and skip the inverse rotation on
-- the key side.
rule VectorDot {
    when: VectorDot(query, block)

    requires: query.count = config.head_dim

    let q_rotated = RHT_forward(query.data, config.head_dim, config.seed)
    let k_codebook = reconstruct_codebook(block, turbo_kv_4b_codebook)
    let dot_result = dot_product(q_rotated, k_codebook) * block.norm

    ensures: result = dot_result
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants
-- ============================================================

-- Distribution caveat: [PAPER] §3 distortion bound assumes the
-- input follows the distribution the codebook was trained on.
-- [QUANT.CPP]'s Gaussian(0,1) codebook + max_abs rescale
-- approximates this across a range of inputs; quality can fall
-- outside the budget for adversarial one-hot-like inputs. Budget
-- of 0.1 covers empirical worst-case on Qwen3.5 KV activations
-- ([QUANT.CPP] PHASE24 measurement; rel_err 0.083 observed).
invariant ReconstructionPreservesNorm {
    for block in QuantizedHeads:
        let reconstructed = DequantizeHead(block)
        abs(L2_norm(reconstructed.data) - block.norm) <= block.norm * config.reconstruction_rel_error
}

-- [PAPER] §3 orthogonality: <a, b> = <RHT(a), RHT(b)>. The
-- paper's entire distortion bound rests on this. The FHT+signs
-- construction (our port + [QUANT.CPP]) satisfies it exactly in
-- the math; floating-point accumulation adds ~log2(d) × fp32_eps
-- drift per the turbo_kv_4b_backend.allium tolerance budget.
invariant RHTOrthogonality {
    for a in Tensors:
        for b in Tensors:
            let a_rot = RHT_forward(a.data, a.count, config.seed)
            let b_rot = RHT_forward(b.data, b.count, config.seed)
            dot_product(a_rot, b_rot) = dot_product(a.data, b.data)
}

invariant RHTIsSelfInverse {
    for v in Tensors:
        let rotated = RHT_forward(v.data, v.count, config.seed)
        let restored = RHT_inverse(rotated, v.count, config.seed)
        restored = v.data
}

-- [PAPER] §3 Lloyd-Max optimality: the chosen centroid minimises
-- MSE distortion for the post-rotation distribution. Distributional
-- mismatch between the port's codebook training (Gaussian(0,1))
-- and input (unit-sphere-rotated, distribution varies with d)
-- means this invariant holds locally (within a batch of similar
-- inputs) but not necessarily globally.
invariant NearestCentroidMinimizesError {
    for x in ScaledValues:
        for cb in Codebooks:
            let best = find_nearest(x, cb.entries)
            for other in cb.entries:
                abs(x - best) <= abs(x - other)
}

invariant DeterministicSeed {
    config.seed = 305419896
}

invariant HeadDimIsPowerOfTwo {
    is_power_of_two(config.head_dim) and config.head_dim > 0
}

invariant IndicesInBounds {
    for block in QuantizedHeads:
        for idx in block.indices:
            idx >= 0 and idx < config.codebook_size
}

-- ============================================================
-- Implementation notes
-- ============================================================

-- Black-box helpers: sum_of_squares, sqrt, scaled, scale,
-- scaled_vector, scaled_codebook, find_nearest, lookup_indices,
-- floor_pow2, apply_sign_flip, walsh_hadamard_transform,
-- dot_product, max_abs, abs, is_power_of_two.
-- C reference: llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-turbo-kv.c.
-- Original C reference: quant.cpp/src/core/tq_turbo_kv.c (GPL-2.0
-- Apache-2.0 — attribution in ggml-turbo-kv.h header comment).
--
-- This spec describes the CORE algorithm. Sibling improvement
-- specs layer on the community extensions documented in open
-- questions:
--
--   turbo_kv_residual_window.allium  — [TONBI-V3] fp16 rolling
--                                      window for recent N tokens,
--                                      bypasses quantisation
--   turbo_kv_asymmetric.allium       — [PAPER §4] + [TONBI-V3]
--                                      K=6/V=4 or K=8/V=4 bit
--                                      allocation for attention
--                                      quality
--   turbo_kv_layer_adaptive.allium   — [TONBI-V3] protected early /
--                                      late layers at higher bits
--   turbo_kv_outliers.allium         — [QUANT.CPP] 4bo / 3bo
--                                      variants: 8 outlier dims
--                                      stored verbatim as fp16
--
-- Each improvement spec cites measurement evidence from its
-- upstream source. Together they define the SOTA target. Weed
-- passes against the llama.cpp port will surface which
-- improvements are not yet implemented.
